the political functioning

00:01:13.710 --> 00:01:17.180
of national security and
the policing of dissent.

00:01:17.180 --> 00:01:19.050
And I'm also the
co-founder and director

00:01:19.050 --> 00:01:21.810
of the nonprofit transparency
organization, Property

00:01:21.810 --> 00:01:23.460
of the People.

00:01:23.460 --> 00:01:26.910
So I'm at Google,
so I'm going to give

00:01:26.910 --> 00:01:31.140
a talk about search protocols.

00:01:31.140 --> 00:01:37.170
This is a talk about the FBI,
record systems, and democracy,

00:01:37.170 --> 00:01:40.290
but first, we're going to take
just a little trip down memory

00:01:40.290 --> 00:01:42.472
lane.

00:01:42.472 --> 00:01:43.680
So I've always liked animals.

00:01:43.680 --> 00:01:46.170
Here is me as a little
kid with a goat.

00:01:46.170 --> 00:01:48.360
And I got into radical
politics and punk rock

00:01:48.360 --> 00:01:49.320
at a very early age.

00:01:49.320 --> 00:01:52.480
Here is me in eighth grade.

00:01:52.480 --> 00:01:54.300
And around the same
time, influenced

00:01:54.300 --> 00:01:58.890
by punk rock and radical
politics, I became vegetarian,

00:01:58.890 --> 00:02:02.467
and then a few years
later, I became vegan.

00:02:02.467 --> 00:02:04.050
Learning about how
animals are treated

00:02:04.050 --> 00:02:06.600
on factory farms, confined
in spaces so small

00:02:06.600 --> 00:02:11.140
they can't stand, turn
around, or spread their limbs.

00:02:11.140 --> 00:02:13.900
And this had a big impact on me.

00:02:13.900 --> 00:02:18.900
And so I grew up in DC
and then I went to college

00:02:18.900 --> 00:02:20.730
at NYU for undergrad.

00:02:20.730 --> 00:02:26.730
And while in New York, I started
coordinating above ground

00:02:26.730 --> 00:02:30.240
direct action campaigns-- civil
disobedience style campaigns.

00:02:30.240 --> 00:02:32.680
This is my first arrest.

00:02:32.680 --> 00:02:35.544
I'm not the first guy
but the second guy.

00:02:35.544 --> 00:02:36.960
We're locked in
these metal pipes.

00:02:36.960 --> 00:02:39.690
This is the ramp to
Ringling Brothers' circus.

00:02:39.690 --> 00:02:42.990
We are preventing the elephants
from getting into the circus,

00:02:42.990 --> 00:02:44.610
shutting down the circus.

00:02:44.610 --> 00:02:46.410
They weren't able
to get in but they

00:02:46.410 --> 00:02:50.880
were able to stand above us and
the ring folks kept them there

00:02:50.880 --> 00:02:55.400
until they urinated on us and we
marinated for hours in elephant

00:02:55.400 --> 00:02:59.070
urine, and then we were brought
into jail in southeast DC.

00:02:59.070 --> 00:03:03.180
Stinking of elephant
urine is quite something.

00:03:03.180 --> 00:03:05.910
At NYU, I coordinated a takeover
of the president's office

00:03:05.910 --> 00:03:10.410
to shut down a laboratory where
they were forcing chimpanzees

00:03:10.410 --> 00:03:12.520
to smoke crack.

00:03:12.520 --> 00:03:14.670
Here I am locked inside
a concrete barrel

00:03:14.670 --> 00:03:17.790
to protest the sale of fur.

00:03:17.790 --> 00:03:20.451
Here is another shot of that.

00:03:20.451 --> 00:03:22.200
This is what it looks
like getting it out.

00:03:22.200 --> 00:03:26.070
They have to use
jackhammers and--

00:03:26.070 --> 00:03:30.360
and you know, when I left
New York, I moved to Hawaii

00:03:30.360 --> 00:03:33.420
and co-coordinated a campaign
to shut down a captive dolphin

00:03:33.420 --> 00:03:34.680
facility in a shopping mall.

00:03:34.680 --> 00:03:37.860
We were making
surfboard protests.

00:03:37.860 --> 00:03:41.860
Here, I sabotaged whale
hunts riding jet skis,

00:03:41.860 --> 00:03:44.640
in between the gunboats
and the whales.

00:03:44.640 --> 00:03:49.750
And so this is all in the mid
'90s, late '90s, early 2000s.

00:03:49.750 --> 00:03:52.350
And then, around 2002, along
with some other activists

00:03:52.350 --> 00:03:54.300
who I'd worked
with for some time,

00:03:54.300 --> 00:03:59.130
I co-coordinated a year-long
undercover investigation

00:03:59.130 --> 00:04:01.770
of foie gras-producing
factory farms in New York

00:04:01.770 --> 00:04:04.770
and in California and we openly
rescued a number of animals

00:04:04.770 --> 00:04:06.720
from those farms.

00:04:06.720 --> 00:04:09.630
Here's me rescuing
one of the ducks

00:04:09.630 --> 00:04:14.250
from a foie gras factory
farm in New York.

00:04:14.250 --> 00:04:15.680
We made a documentary about it.

00:04:15.680 --> 00:04:19.560
I did go to NYU
undergrad for film.

00:04:19.560 --> 00:04:27.720
And we got prosecuted for
doing this in 2003 and 2004.

00:04:27.720 --> 00:04:29.400
We were facing felony
burglary charges.

00:04:29.400 --> 00:04:30.660
This is Sarahjane Blum.

00:04:30.660 --> 00:04:35.269
She and I were facing felony
burglary charges in New York.

00:04:35.269 --> 00:04:36.810
I was getting a
master's degree in DC

00:04:36.810 --> 00:04:38.435
at the time in modern
American history.

00:04:40.680 --> 00:04:44.640
And to my surprise, we ended
up beating the charges.

00:04:44.640 --> 00:04:52.050
And so this brings us up to 2004
and I had a bit of a dilemma,

00:04:52.050 --> 00:04:55.200
because in 2004, there was
this massive legislative

00:04:55.200 --> 00:04:59.060
and legal and
prosecutorial shift.

00:04:59.060 --> 00:05:02.169
In 2004, the FBI designated
the animal rights

00:05:02.169 --> 00:05:04.710
and environmental movements to
the number one domestic terror

00:05:04.710 --> 00:05:06.792
threats in the United
States, despite the fact

00:05:06.792 --> 00:05:08.250
that neither of
these movements has

00:05:08.250 --> 00:05:11.140
ever physically injured a single
person once in this country.

00:05:11.140 --> 00:05:14.010
And yet, number one
domestic terror threat.

00:05:14.010 --> 00:05:16.560
Not militia movements,
white power movements,

00:05:16.560 --> 00:05:19.380
anti-abortion folks--
people who kill people,

00:05:19.380 --> 00:05:20.880
people who try to kill people--

00:05:20.880 --> 00:05:24.660
but puppy huggers
and tree huggers.

00:05:24.660 --> 00:05:28.050
And there was also, shortly
after that, the passage

00:05:28.050 --> 00:05:30.060
of the Animal Enterprise
Terrorism Act,

00:05:30.060 --> 00:05:34.230
or AETA, which is a piece of
pernicious post-911 legislation

00:05:34.230 --> 00:05:36.690
that's essentially a Patriot
Act explicitly targeting

00:05:36.690 --> 00:05:39.960
animal rights and
environmental protesters.

00:05:39.960 --> 00:05:42.000
And there was also
the prosecution

00:05:42.000 --> 00:05:44.220
of some of my closest
friends and colleagues

00:05:44.220 --> 00:05:47.130
under federal felony terrorism
charges for running an animal

00:05:47.130 --> 00:05:49.100
rights website.

00:05:49.100 --> 00:05:50.370
They are known as the SHAC 7.

00:05:50.370 --> 00:05:52.980
I kid you not.

00:05:52.980 --> 00:05:56.315
And all of this was part of
what journalist Will Potter has

00:05:56.315 --> 00:05:58.440
termed "the green scare"--
the disproportionate use

00:05:58.440 --> 00:06:00.690
of the rhetoric and apparatus
of national security

00:06:00.690 --> 00:06:02.820
to marginalize animal
rights activists

00:06:02.820 --> 00:06:06.750
and environmental activists
as threats to the state.

00:06:06.750 --> 00:06:09.210
Will's excellent book,
"Green is the New Red,"

00:06:09.210 --> 00:06:14.460
talks about this if you're
interested in learning more.

00:06:14.460 --> 00:06:18.212
So, as I said, I had
something of a dilemma.

00:06:18.212 --> 00:06:20.670
I didn't know what to do next
because the model of activism

00:06:20.670 --> 00:06:23.269
that I'd pursued, along
with many other folks,

00:06:23.269 --> 00:06:24.810
for the previous
decade with impunity

00:06:24.810 --> 00:06:28.110
was overnight terrorism.

00:06:28.110 --> 00:06:31.130
And so, like lots of folks who
don't know what to do next,

00:06:31.130 --> 00:06:37.230
I stayed in grad school
and I started work on a PhD

00:06:37.230 --> 00:06:39.480
at the University of California
Santa Barbara, program

00:06:39.480 --> 00:06:41.650
in the history of
science, trying

00:06:41.650 --> 00:06:44.170
to figure out how we got
to this state of affairs.

00:06:44.170 --> 00:06:49.440
And then I went over
to MIT, where I am now,

00:06:49.440 --> 00:06:52.560
finishing up my PhD there.

00:06:52.560 --> 00:06:55.890
And so, you know,
my dissertation--

00:06:55.890 --> 00:06:58.200
I'm interested in how we got
to this state of affairs.

00:06:58.200 --> 00:07:00.450
How did the FBI come to
understand the animal rights

00:07:00.450 --> 00:07:02.400
and environmental movements as
the number one domestic terror

00:07:02.400 --> 00:07:03.220
threats in the country?

00:07:03.220 --> 00:07:04.490
How did the animal rights
and environmental movements

00:07:04.490 --> 00:07:06.304
first come to the
attention of the FBI?

00:07:06.304 --> 00:07:08.220
What was the role of
industry in this process?

00:07:08.220 --> 00:07:11.640
And again, number one
domestic terror threat?

00:07:11.640 --> 00:07:18.000
So my professional
training as an historian

00:07:18.000 --> 00:07:21.510
is primarily archival research--
at least it was at that time.

00:07:21.510 --> 00:07:23.490
And while some portions
of my dissertation--

00:07:23.490 --> 00:07:25.960
I'm looking at a 100-year span
of the use of the rhetoric

00:07:25.960 --> 00:07:29.380
and apparatus to target animal
protectionists in the United

00:07:29.380 --> 00:07:29.880
States--

00:07:29.880 --> 00:07:32.880
some of it, I was
able to use archival--

00:07:32.880 --> 00:07:36.360
you know, standard
historian's archival tools.

00:07:36.360 --> 00:07:37.969
But for the more
modern stuff, so

00:07:37.969 --> 00:07:40.260
starting with the emergence
of the modern animal rights

00:07:40.260 --> 00:07:44.790
movement in the 1970s and
certainly with FBI involvement,

00:07:44.790 --> 00:07:47.760
there's not really going
to be any archives that

00:07:47.760 --> 00:07:49.180
are going to be of use here.

00:07:49.180 --> 00:07:50.672
So I realized I would need--

00:07:50.672 --> 00:07:53.130
I was like, I'll try to use
the Freedom of Information Act.

00:07:53.130 --> 00:07:57.270
I didn't know anything
about FOIA at the time,

00:07:57.270 --> 00:08:00.960
but I did know that it was
going to be the only way that I

00:08:00.960 --> 00:08:03.150
might be able to get anything.

00:08:03.150 --> 00:08:05.550
So, you know, not knowing
anything about FOIA,

00:08:05.550 --> 00:08:07.425
I shot off a FOIA
request to the FBI

00:08:07.425 --> 00:08:10.260
and I asked for records on me.

00:08:10.260 --> 00:08:12.630
And the FBI turned
around and they

00:08:12.630 --> 00:08:15.130
said they don't have anything.

00:08:15.130 --> 00:08:18.632
They actually said they
can't find anything, but--

00:08:18.632 --> 00:08:20.965
no records responsive to your
FOIA request were located.

00:08:23.650 --> 00:08:25.300
I'll be honest, I
was a little hurt.

00:08:25.300 --> 00:08:28.690
You know, I thought I was
more important than that,

00:08:28.690 --> 00:08:30.010
but that's all right, you know?

00:08:30.010 --> 00:08:30.690
I could take it.

00:08:30.690 --> 00:08:32.065
It's fine.

00:08:32.065 --> 00:08:32.690
It's all right.

00:08:32.690 --> 00:08:33.659
It's all right.

00:08:33.659 --> 00:08:35.950
But I really wanted records
and I was looking for a way

00:08:35.950 --> 00:08:41.530
in and so Sarahjane Blum, the
activist who I pointed out

00:08:41.530 --> 00:08:44.740
earlier, when we were arrested
for the foie gras undercover

00:08:44.740 --> 00:08:49.762
investigation and open
rescue back in '03--

00:08:49.762 --> 00:08:51.220
we were arrested
for the same thing

00:08:51.220 --> 00:08:52.765
but we were arrested separately.

00:08:52.765 --> 00:08:54.640
I was arrested just by
New York State Police,

00:08:54.640 --> 00:08:56.015
but when Sarah
Jane was arrested,

00:08:56.015 --> 00:08:58.569
she was arrested by New York
State Police and an FBI agent.

00:08:58.569 --> 00:09:00.610
So I was like, OK, well
I'm not important enough.

00:09:00.610 --> 00:09:04.130
I wasn't important enough
to warrant an FBI file,

00:09:04.130 --> 00:09:05.350
but Sarah Jane obviously was.

00:09:05.350 --> 00:09:07.150
I mean, there was
an FBI agent there.

00:09:07.150 --> 00:09:10.480
So she kindly gave me
her written permission--

00:09:10.480 --> 00:09:11.110
her consent--

00:09:11.110 --> 00:09:12.790
to submit a request about her.

00:09:12.790 --> 00:09:14.380
That doesn't mean the FBI
has to give me her files,

00:09:14.380 --> 00:09:16.963
it just means they can't use her
personal privacy as an excuse

00:09:16.963 --> 00:09:18.290
to withhold them from me.

00:09:18.290 --> 00:09:20.030
And so I submitted
the request on her.

00:09:20.030 --> 00:09:23.100
And again, the
results came back.

00:09:23.100 --> 00:09:24.070
Same thing.

00:09:24.070 --> 00:09:25.740
Hey, look, we couldn't
find anything.

00:09:25.740 --> 00:09:29.230
I was like, well, that's
weird but all right.

00:09:29.230 --> 00:09:30.870
I was like, OK, I know what.

00:09:30.870 --> 00:09:32.492
I have this other
friend of mine.

00:09:32.492 --> 00:09:34.200
The FBI has chased
her around the country

00:09:34.200 --> 00:09:35.340
with a warrant for her DNA.

00:09:35.340 --> 00:09:37.710
They've raided her storage
unit on multiple occasions.

00:09:37.710 --> 00:09:39.690
They've arrested her
on multiple occasions.

00:09:39.690 --> 00:09:41.700
She's done time for
grand jury resistance.

00:09:41.700 --> 00:09:44.580
The FBI is obsessed
with this woman--

00:09:44.580 --> 00:09:46.500
with this wonderful
person and activist.

00:09:46.500 --> 00:09:47.708
The FBI is obsessed with her.

00:09:47.708 --> 00:09:50.730
She definitely has a file
and, like, a giant file.

00:09:50.730 --> 00:09:52.680
So she kindly gave me
her written consent

00:09:52.680 --> 00:09:53.910
to submit a request on her.

00:09:53.910 --> 00:09:56.492
So I was like, all right, now
we're going to get somewhere.

00:09:56.492 --> 00:09:58.090
Eh, the same thing happens.

00:09:58.090 --> 00:10:00.465
They turn around and was like,
no, I don't have anything.

00:10:00.465 --> 00:10:01.900
I was like, oh, I get it.

00:10:01.900 --> 00:10:02.400
I'm sorry.

00:10:02.400 --> 00:10:04.560
This is my fault.
This is my bad.

00:10:04.560 --> 00:10:07.950
I'm being lied to and I was
naive and didn't get it.

00:10:07.950 --> 00:10:11.490
I mean, the thing is, I hated
the FBI basically forever.

00:10:11.490 --> 00:10:14.250
I grew up as a punk rock kid
listening to the Dead Kennedys.

00:10:14.250 --> 00:10:16.890
My first research paper ever
was in eighth grade about Sacco

00:10:16.890 --> 00:10:18.390
and Vanzetti, two
Italian anarchists

00:10:18.390 --> 00:10:23.090
who were ultimately murdered
by what would become the FBI--

00:10:23.090 --> 00:10:26.787
or, well, they were executed
by the state and the FBI was--

00:10:26.787 --> 00:10:28.620
or the Bureau of
Investigation at the time--

00:10:28.620 --> 00:10:29.994
was heavily involved.

00:10:29.994 --> 00:10:31.410
I read Brian Glick's
"War at Home"

00:10:31.410 --> 00:10:34.080
about the FBI's COINTELPRO or
counterintelligence programs

00:10:34.080 --> 00:10:36.190
where the FBI targeted
the civil rights

00:10:36.190 --> 00:10:37.710
movements, the black
power movement,

00:10:37.710 --> 00:10:38.670
the anti-war movement.

00:10:38.670 --> 00:10:41.070
I read that when it came out
when I was in eighth grade.

00:10:41.070 --> 00:10:43.320
So I hated the FBI forever,
but for some reason,

00:10:43.320 --> 00:10:46.650
I had naively believed
that the FBI RIDS,

00:10:46.650 --> 00:10:48.900
the Records/Information
Dissemination Section--

00:10:48.900 --> 00:10:51.047
that's their FOIA
division at the FBI--

00:10:51.047 --> 00:10:55.470
I naively believed that FBI
RIDS, their FOIA division,

00:10:55.470 --> 00:10:59.260
would be not mission-driven
like the rest of the FBI

00:10:59.260 --> 00:11:01.890
but just sort of a
bureaucratic outpost.

00:11:01.890 --> 00:11:04.390
I was like, you know, when
I got back the third denial

00:11:04.390 --> 00:11:07.130
letter, my friend who I know
she's got a massive file,

00:11:07.130 --> 00:11:08.130
it's like, OK, I get it.

00:11:08.130 --> 00:11:10.050
This is my fault.
I'm being lied to.

00:11:10.050 --> 00:11:11.110
This is my bad.

00:11:11.110 --> 00:11:17.750
And no one likes being lied
to, but I get real twitchy

00:11:17.750 --> 00:11:18.830
about it.

00:11:18.830 --> 00:11:21.590
And you know, we
all have qualities

00:11:21.590 --> 00:11:23.420
that at some times
in our lives prove

00:11:23.420 --> 00:11:26.960
more adaptive or maladaptive,
depending on the circumstances,

00:11:26.960 --> 00:11:30.200
and my OCD need for
conflict and contempt

00:11:30.200 --> 00:11:32.280
for federal
intelligence agencies,

00:11:32.280 --> 00:11:37.320
it's not always been the most
conducive to positive outcomes.

00:11:37.320 --> 00:11:39.420
But in this case, it
worked out very well.

00:11:39.420 --> 00:11:41.390
And I started to become
obsessed not only

00:11:41.390 --> 00:11:42.950
with trying to get records
about FBI campaigns

00:11:42.950 --> 00:11:45.158
against the animal rights
and environmental movements

00:11:45.158 --> 00:11:48.560
but trying to map out the
nature of FBI noncompliance

00:11:48.560 --> 00:11:50.240
with the Freedom
of Information Act

00:11:50.240 --> 00:11:55.180
because you know, the Freedom of
Information Act is federal law

00:11:55.180 --> 00:11:57.340
and the FBI is the leading
federal law enforcement

00:11:57.340 --> 00:11:59.136
agency in the country
and this means

00:11:59.136 --> 00:12:00.760
we have the outrageous
state of affairs

00:12:00.760 --> 00:12:02.170
in which the leading
federal law enforcement

00:12:02.170 --> 00:12:04.128
agency in the country is
in routine in flagrant

00:12:04.128 --> 00:12:05.930
violation of federal law.

00:12:05.930 --> 00:12:07.310
And the question is, how?

00:12:07.310 --> 00:12:11.110
How is the FBI systematically
avoiding compliance

00:12:11.110 --> 00:12:12.700
with the Freedom
of Information Act?

00:12:12.700 --> 00:12:14.200
And so that question
increasingly

00:12:14.200 --> 00:12:16.810
became as and then
more important to me

00:12:16.810 --> 00:12:19.330
than the original questions I
was asking about FBI campaigns

00:12:19.330 --> 00:12:21.413
against animal rights and
environmental movements.

00:12:21.413 --> 00:12:23.719
And so I started submitting
hundreds and hundreds

00:12:23.719 --> 00:12:24.760
of experimental requests.

00:12:24.760 --> 00:12:27.460
I got signed privacy waivers
from 250 leading animal rights

00:12:27.460 --> 00:12:29.460
activists from the
