00:14:04.870 --> 00:14:12.330
Well, either way, so here I am.

00:14:12.330 --> 00:14:17.120
So we'll say hi to Ihi again.

00:14:17.120 --> 00:14:19.900
Yeah.

00:14:19.900 --> 00:14:23.519
And the FBI said,
oh, that's real cute.

00:14:23.519 --> 00:14:24.310
You're very clever.

00:14:24.310 --> 00:14:24.850
Look at you.

00:14:24.850 --> 00:14:27.700
You've got all these documents.

00:14:27.700 --> 00:14:29.350
You should be very
proud of yourself.

00:14:29.350 --> 00:14:30.380
Watch what we can do.

00:14:30.380 --> 00:14:32.740
And then they sat on their
hands because the Freedom

00:14:32.740 --> 00:14:35.406
of Information Act is one of the
most under-appreciated elements

00:14:35.406 --> 00:14:36.880
of the entire
American experiment.

00:14:36.880 --> 00:14:38.170
The notion that the
records of government

00:14:38.170 --> 00:14:39.340
are the property of
the people and all

00:14:39.340 --> 00:14:42.100
we need to do to get them is
to ask for them is radically

00:14:42.100 --> 00:14:43.680
democratic but FOIA is broken.

00:14:43.680 --> 00:14:45.430
And one of the main
reasons FOIA is broken

00:14:45.430 --> 00:14:47.480
is that there are no
penalties for noncompliance.

00:14:47.480 --> 00:14:48.970
So an agency that
doesn't want to comply,

00:14:48.970 --> 00:14:50.470
or in the case of
the FBI, an agency

00:14:50.470 --> 00:14:54.310
that is overtly hostile to the
Freedom of Information Act,

00:14:54.310 --> 00:14:55.600
has no incentive to comply.

00:14:55.600 --> 00:14:57.100
And so they just
sat on their hands.

00:14:57.100 --> 00:14:58.480
And an agency only
has 20 working days

00:14:58.480 --> 00:14:59.590
to comply with a request--

00:14:59.590 --> 00:15:02.190
not to give me the records
but to process the request--

00:15:02.190 --> 00:15:04.730
and they sat on these
requests for years.

00:15:04.730 --> 00:15:05.494
So I sued.

00:15:05.494 --> 00:15:07.660
I mean, FOIA's toothless
but it has this baby tooth.

00:15:07.660 --> 00:15:09.243
There's no penalties
for noncompliance

00:15:09.243 --> 00:15:11.330
but you can sue an agency
for failure to comply.

00:15:11.330 --> 00:15:16.390
So I teamed up with Jeffrey
Light, who is a brilliant FOIA

00:15:16.390 --> 00:15:21.190
specialist attorney with
politics similar to my own,

00:15:21.190 --> 00:15:25.690
and we sued the FBI for
failure to comply with FOIA

00:15:25.690 --> 00:15:29.206
because they took
way, way, way too long

00:15:29.206 --> 00:15:31.210
to comply with my request--

00:15:31.210 --> 00:15:32.460
or my requests.

00:15:32.460 --> 00:15:34.810
And sorry, here.

00:15:34.810 --> 00:15:36.220
That's a little awkward.

00:15:40.660 --> 00:15:41.170
Yeah.

00:15:41.170 --> 00:15:43.510
And so what's supposed to
happen in a circumstance

00:15:43.510 --> 00:15:46.300
like this is you go in and
the judge is like, OK, FBI,

00:15:46.300 --> 00:15:48.008
you're obviously in
violation of the law.

00:15:48.008 --> 00:15:50.110
When are you going to comply?

00:15:50.110 --> 00:15:52.199
Not when are you going
to give the documents

00:15:52.199 --> 00:15:54.740
but when are you going to figure
out what you're going to do?

00:15:54.740 --> 00:15:58.947
And instead of negotiating
with me via my counsel--

00:15:58.947 --> 00:16:01.030
you know, they want to do
it in a year and a half.

00:16:01.030 --> 00:16:02.440
I want it yesterday.

00:16:02.440 --> 00:16:05.017
Maybe we'll agree on a
calendar of nine months.

00:16:05.017 --> 00:16:07.600
The FBI comes in and invokes the
nuclear option of a FOIA case

00:16:07.600 --> 00:16:08.970
called an open America state.

00:16:08.970 --> 00:16:10.690
They say they want seven years--

00:16:10.690 --> 00:16:12.580
actually unprecedented--
to just think

00:16:12.580 --> 00:16:16.300
about how to respond
to my FOIA requests.

00:16:16.300 --> 00:16:18.670
Doing so, they are relying on--

00:16:18.670 --> 00:16:22.090
they revived a Cold
War-era FOIA secrecy

00:16:22.090 --> 00:16:25.720
doctrine known as the
Mosaic Theory of Information

00:16:25.720 --> 00:16:30.080
in order to argue that my MIT
dissertation FOIA research

00:16:30.080 --> 00:16:34.554
methodologies are themselves
a threat to national security,

00:16:34.554 --> 00:16:36.970
which is the nicest thing that
anyone's ever said about me

00:16:36.970 --> 00:16:42.377
and will look great on the cover
of the book, but keep in mind,

00:16:42.377 --> 00:16:44.710
the FBI is not arguing that
the release of the documents

00:16:44.710 --> 00:16:47.650
that I've requested would
threaten national security

00:16:47.650 --> 00:16:49.510
but rather that
deciding whether or not

00:16:49.510 --> 00:16:52.640
to release the
documents to me would

00:16:52.640 --> 00:16:55.310
threaten national security.

00:16:55.310 --> 00:16:58.250
And further, the purported
risk to national security

00:16:58.250 --> 00:17:00.470
posed by my
dissertation research

00:17:00.470 --> 00:17:04.400
is ostensibly so grave that the
FBI can't even talk about it.

00:17:04.400 --> 00:17:08.481
Indeed, the FBI's primary
support for its argument

00:17:08.481 --> 00:17:10.689
came in the form of an ex
parte in camera declaration

00:17:10.689 --> 00:17:13.069
to a secret letter from the
counter-terrorism division

00:17:13.069 --> 00:17:17.530
of the FBI to the judge
about why they can't tell us

00:17:17.530 --> 00:17:19.530
why my FOIA dissertation
research methodology is

00:17:19.530 --> 00:17:22.011
a threat to national security.

00:17:22.011 --> 00:17:24.260
And this is an especially
circular and Kafkaesque line

00:17:24.260 --> 00:17:25.550
of argument.

00:17:25.550 --> 00:17:27.527
The FBI considers it a
national security threat

00:17:27.527 --> 00:17:29.360
to make public its
reasoning for considering

00:17:29.360 --> 00:17:31.970
it a national security threat
to use federal law to request

00:17:31.970 --> 00:17:33.440
information about
the FBI's deeply

00:17:33.440 --> 00:17:35.945
problematic understanding of
national security threats.

00:17:42.090 --> 00:17:47.120
And it's important to remember
that though the FBI doesn't

00:17:47.120 --> 00:17:51.320
want damning records about
it coming out whether they

00:17:51.320 --> 00:17:53.584
be about campaigns against
the animal rights movement,

00:17:53.584 --> 00:17:55.250
the environmental
movement, or whatever,

00:17:55.250 --> 00:17:56.840
that's not what this
is really about.

00:17:56.840 --> 00:17:58.580
Rather, the FBI's
core motivation

00:17:58.580 --> 00:18:01.610
here is maintaining
its functional immunity

00:18:01.610 --> 00:18:05.150
from the Freedom
of Information Act.

00:18:05.150 --> 00:18:07.940
And this brings us to
FBI record systems.

00:18:07.940 --> 00:18:13.640
So one of the core ways that
the FBI maintains its immunity

00:18:13.640 --> 00:18:18.410
from FOIA is through its
failure-by-design FOIA search

00:18:18.410 --> 00:18:20.000
protocols.

00:18:20.000 --> 00:18:24.110
Since its earliest days, the
FBI has used political dissent

00:18:24.110 --> 00:18:26.750
as a threat, and since the
Freedom of Information Act

00:18:26.750 --> 00:18:30.020
was first amended in
1974 to apply to the FBI

00:18:30.020 --> 00:18:32.650
and other intelligence
agencies, the FBI

00:18:32.650 --> 00:18:34.670
has understood FOIA
in the same light--

00:18:34.670 --> 00:18:38.600
as a threat-- and has done
functionally everything

00:18:38.600 --> 00:18:41.510
within their power
to avoid compliance.

00:18:41.510 --> 00:18:45.689
Indeed, in 2009, the
National Security Archive--

00:18:45.689 --> 00:18:47.480
a great transparency
organization based out

00:18:47.480 --> 00:18:49.520
of George Washington
University--

00:18:49.520 --> 00:18:54.057
gave the FBI its hoax
Rosemary Award for "worst

00:18:54.057 --> 00:18:55.640
Freedom of Information
Act performance

00:18:55.640 --> 00:18:59.420
by a federal agency"
for "outstandingly bad

00:18:59.420 --> 00:19:00.830
responsiveness to
the public that

00:19:00.830 --> 00:19:03.410
flaunts the letter and spirit
of the Freedom of Information

00:19:03.410 --> 00:19:04.860
Act."

00:19:04.860 --> 00:19:10.280
In like spirit, a related 2009
"Associated Press" article

00:19:10.280 --> 00:19:12.770
decried FBI abuses
of FOIA and it

00:19:12.770 --> 00:19:15.080
opened by asserting, "if
information were a river,

00:19:15.080 --> 00:19:17.840
the FBI would be a dam."

00:19:17.840 --> 00:19:20.540
So, over the years, the FBI
has established countless means

00:19:20.540 --> 00:19:22.760
by which to avoid
compliance with FOIA.

00:19:22.760 --> 00:19:25.190
One of the chief means by
which the FBI accomplishes

00:19:25.190 --> 00:19:28.870
this is to search for
records in such a way

00:19:28.870 --> 00:19:32.290
that the search routinely
fails by design.

00:19:32.290 --> 00:19:34.840
The National Security
Archives 2009 study

00:19:34.840 --> 00:19:36.730
found that on
average, the FBI fails

00:19:36.730 --> 00:19:42.140
to locate any records at all
for every two out of three FOIA

00:19:42.140 --> 00:19:43.720
requests.

00:19:43.720 --> 00:19:46.710
That's a failure rate
five times higher

00:19:46.710 --> 00:19:48.231
than other agencies on average.

00:19:48.231 --> 00:19:49.980
And you could say,
well maybe the FBI just

00:19:49.980 --> 00:19:53.470
gets a lot of crappy requests.

00:19:53.470 --> 00:19:55.156
That's not-- that
would be wrong.

00:19:55.156 --> 00:19:57.280
I mean, I'm sure they get
a lot of crappy requests,

00:19:57.280 --> 00:19:59.660
but that is not what
is happening here.

00:19:59.660 --> 00:20:02.120
So, the Freedom of
Information Act, the statute,

00:20:02.120 --> 00:20:04.780
it doesn't require an
agency to locate records.

00:20:04.780 --> 00:20:08.620
It requires an agency to conduct
a search reasonably calculated

00:20:08.620 --> 00:20:12.800
to locate responsive records.

00:20:12.800 --> 00:20:19.100
And by utilizing a deliberately
deficient FOIA search

00:20:19.100 --> 00:20:20.990
methodology, the
FBI superficially

00:20:20.990 --> 00:20:23.022
appears to be in
compliance with FOIA

00:20:23.022 --> 00:20:24.980
without having to actually
locate and therefore

00:20:24.980 --> 00:20:28.400
potentially release
many records.

00:20:28.400 --> 00:20:31.400
So how exactly does this work?

00:20:31.400 --> 00:20:35.460
Today we're going to take
a look at a key part of it.

00:20:35.460 --> 00:20:39.420
So FBI RIDS-- the
FOIA division at FBI--

00:20:39.420 --> 00:20:43.610
asserts that nearly all records
responsive to nearly all FOIA

00:20:43.610 --> 00:20:47.270
requests will be maintained
within the FBI's Central

00:20:47.270 --> 00:20:51.450
Records System, or CRS.

00:20:51.450 --> 00:20:54.270
And this is problematic
on a number of levels.

00:20:54.270 --> 00:20:57.930
There are many FBI records that
are not contained in the CRS,

00:20:57.930 --> 00:21:01.620
including the ELSUR indices--
the electronic surveillance

00:21:01.620 --> 00:21:03.060
records.

00:21:03.060 --> 00:21:06.840
The FBI's indices for searching
for electronic surveillance

00:21:06.840 --> 00:21:11.910
records are separate from the
CRS and cannot be searched

00:21:11.910 --> 00:21:13.387
using a CRS search.

00:21:13.387 --> 00:21:14.970
But either way, we're
not really going

00:21:14.970 --> 00:21:16.530
to deal with ELSUR
records right now

00:21:16.530 --> 00:21:19.110
and we're really just going
to be looking at the CRS.

00:21:19.110 --> 00:21:23.770
So the CRS does
have a huge amount

00:21:23.770 --> 00:21:27.570
of records in it-- about 115
million records-- not pages,

00:21:27.570 --> 00:21:28.070
but records.

00:21:28.070 --> 00:21:33.160
It's the FBI's main
investigative database.

00:21:33.160 --> 00:21:35.890
And in fact, it's
basically the same CRS

00:21:35.890 --> 00:21:39.640
that J. Edgar Hoover
helped design in 1921.

00:21:39.640 --> 00:21:42.070
So the FBI got--

00:21:42.070 --> 00:21:45.370
its inception was in 1908 when
the attorney general appointed

00:21:45.370 --> 00:21:47.000
some special agents in 1909.

00:21:47.000 --> 00:21:49.600
It took the name Bureau
of Investigation.

00:21:49.600 --> 00:21:53.860
And between 1909 and 1921,
the Bureau of Investigation

00:21:53.860 --> 00:21:57.160
experimented with a whole number
of records management systems

00:21:57.160 --> 00:21:59.440
and they were all
totally failures.

00:21:59.440 --> 00:22:02.260
In fact, it was so bad that
in 1920, the FBI gave--

00:22:02.260 --> 00:22:05.530
or the Bureau of Investigation--
gave up entirely and just gave

00:22:05.530 --> 00:22:07.660
all of its records to the DOJ.

00:22:07.660 --> 00:22:11.750
In 1921, the DOJ said, no, thank
you, and gave the records back

00:22:11.750 --> 00:22:14.290
to the Bureau of
Investigation, at which point

00:22:14.290 --> 00:22:17.890
J. Edgar Hoover helped
design what ultimately became

00:22:17.890 --> 00:22:19.180
the Central Records System.

00:22:19.180 --> 00:22:22.630
Notably, Hoover's first job
was an entry-level position

00:22:22.630 --> 00:22:26.680
at the Library of Congress,
and so he cared deeply

00:22:26.680 --> 00:22:29.140
about records management
and brought that knowledge

00:22:29.140 --> 00:22:33.990
to bear in designing the
CRS and it's the same CRS

00:22:33.990 --> 00:22:35.632
that we deal with today.

00:22:35.632 --> 00:22:37.090
But those FOIA
requests [INAUDIBLE]

00:22:37.090 --> 00:22:41.390
that is the FBI's main
investigative database.

00:22:41.390 --> 00:22:46.600
So, according to the FBI, the
CRS itself cannot actually be

00:22:46.600 --> 00:22:48.544
searched.

00:22:48.544 --> 00:22:49.960
It's a little
unclear why this is.

00:22:49.960 --> 00:22:56.170
It's probably because the CRS
is in fact a paper database

00:22:56.170 --> 00:22:59.470
of 115 million records.

00:22:59.470 --> 00:23:02.170
And so, to search
the CRS, the FBI

00:23:02.170 --> 00:23:08.360
created something
called the ACS in 1995,

00:23:08.360 --> 00:23:12.700
which more or less mirrors
the CRS and is searchable.

00:23:12.700 --> 00:23:17.800
Between 1921 and 1995,
there's essentially-- well,

00:23:17.800 --> 00:23:20.320
between 1921 and
the early 1970s,

00:23:20.320 --> 00:23:22.810
there was no automated
search capacity.

00:23:22.810 --> 00:23:25.160
Between 1970 and '79,
there was a teeny bit.

00:23:25.160 --> 00:23:30.370
But through '95, there was
extremely little functional

00:23:30.370 --> 00:23:32.410
search capacity of
an automated fashion.

00:23:32.410 --> 00:23:39.220
In '95, the ACS comes in-- the
Automated Case Support system.

00:23:39.220 --> 00:23:42.250
And while the ACS is
definitely better than nothing,

00:23:42.250 --> 00:23:43.720
it is still garbage.

00:23:43.720 --> 00:23:48.040
It is a garbage search platform.

00:23:48.040 --> 00:23:50.560
Indeed, the inherent
deficiencies of the ACS

00:23:50.560 --> 00:23:55.360
are so severe that they extend
well beyond the world of FOIA.

00:23:55.360 --> 00:23:58.060
In 2005, the Department
of Justice's Office

00:23:58.060 --> 00:24:01.180
of the Inspector General
itself concluded that there

00:24:01.180 --> 00:24:03.377
were national security--

00:24:03.377 --> 00:24:04.960
this was the document
I wanted before.

00:24:04.960 --> 00:24:06.710
I apologize for that.

00:24:06.710 --> 00:24:10.140
So here we go.

00:24:10.140 --> 00:24:11.190
What we have here--

00:24:11.190 --> 00:24:17.930
one of the documents that I
got about animal rights stuff

00:24:17.930 --> 00:24:22.520
showed that the FBI considered
pursuing federal terrorism

00:24:22.520 --> 00:24:25.709
charges against people who take
pictures of animals trapped

00:24:25.709 --> 00:24:27.500
in cages so small they
can't stand up, turn

00:24:27.500 --> 00:24:29.340
around, or spread their limbs.

00:24:29.340 --> 00:24:32.000
And the "LA Times"
wrote about it

00:24:32.000 --> 00:24:34.499
and I was certainly
distressed to see my own name

00:24:34.499 --> 00:24:36.290
under the people that
they were considering

00:24:36.290 --> 00:24:38.540
pursuing federal terrorism
charges for taking pictures

00:24:38.540 --> 00:24:40.430
of animals trapped in cages.

00:24:40.430 --> 00:24:48.170
But back to the DOJ
OIG's 2005 report,

00:24:48.170 --> 00:24:52.130
which said that there are
national security implications

00:24:52.130 --> 00:24:55.460
because the FBI is continuing
to rely on the ACS,

00:24:55.460 --> 00:24:57.620
which hampers FBI
agents and analysts

00:24:57.620 --> 00:25:00.410
from adequately searching
and sharing information

00:25:00.410 --> 00:25:03.310
from their investigative files.

00:25:03.310 --> 00:25:07.860
The 2005 DOJ OIG
report further found

00:25:07.860 --> 00:25:11.020
that the need for a new
automated investigative case

00:25:11.020 --> 00:25:14.330
management system to replace the
existing obsolete and limited

00:25:14.330 --> 00:25:17.440
ACS system is vital
to the FBI's ability

00:25:17.440 --> 00:25:19.540
to perform its
mission effectively.

00:25:19.540 --> 00:25:25.000
And the 2005 DOJ OIG report also
further found the critical need

00:25:25.000 --> 00:25:28.030
to replace the ACS, the FBI's
obsolete case management

00:25:28.030 --> 00:25:29.880
system, remains.

00:25:29.880 --> 00:25:31.630
And starkly, the very
first recommendation

00:25:31.630 --> 00:25:37.240
and the conclusion of this
2005 DOJ OIG report was,

00:25:37.240 --> 00:25:39.820
"replace the obsolete
ACS system as quickly

00:25:39.820 --> 00:25:43.480
and cost effectively
as feasible."

00:25:43.480 --> 00:25:47.200
Yet, the FBI
continues to rely upon

00:25:47.200 --> 00:25:51.640
this antiquated, obsolete, and
limited ACS system for FOIA

00:25:51.640 --> 00:25:55.480
search purposes, even while
the FBI has increasingly

00:25:55.480 --> 00:25:59.440
relied upon more modern
non-ACS search platforms

00:25:59.440 --> 00:26:02.560
for its non-FOIA operations.

00:26:02.560 --> 00:26:07.390
Indeed, even the FBI's own
2004 Report to the National

00:26:07.390 --> 00:26:10.030
Commission on Terrorist
Attacks upon the United States,

00:26:10.030 --> 00:26:13.180
the FBI'S counter-terrorism
program since September 2001,

00:26:13.180 --> 00:26:18.040
found that the FBI's grievous
failure to identify or prevent

00:26:18.040 --> 00:26:19.900
the terrorist attacks
of the September 11,

00:26:19.900 --> 00:26:22.660
2001 was in part due to the
woefully deficient nature

00:26:22.660 --> 00:26:24.340
of the ACS.

00:26:24.340 --> 00:26:28.270
Found the FBI's 2004 Report,
on September 11, 2001,

00:26:28.270 --> 00:26:29.770
the Bureau of
Information technology

00:26:29.770 --> 00:26:32.326
was inadequate to support its
counter-terrorism mission.

00:26:32.326 --> 00:26:33.700
A core element to
this deficiency

00:26:33.700 --> 00:26:36.820
was that the FBI had a deficient
information management system.

00:26:36.820 --> 00:26:39.640
The FBI's legacy investigative
information system,

00:26:39.640 --> 00:26:41.890
the Automated Case
Support, or ACS,

00:26:41.890 --> 00:26:44.440
was not very effective in
identifying information

00:26:44.440 --> 00:26:46.240
or supporting investigations.

00:26:46.240 --> 00:26:49.150
So the ACS is so bad
it's partially to blame,

00:26:49.150 --> 00:26:52.060
according to the FBI,
for 9/11, and yet, this

00:26:52.060 --> 00:26:56.530
is still what the FBI is using
for FOIA search purposes.

00:26:56.530 --> 00:26:59.440
Additionally, the FBI's
own actions further

00:26:59.440 --> 00:27:01.960
demonstrate that
the Bureau itself

00:27:01.960 --> 00:27:04.750
believes reliance
on ACS searches

00:27:04.750 --> 00:27:06.700
is woefully insufficient.

00:27:06.700 --> 00:27:09.190
The FBI has lobbied
for and received

00:27:09.190 --> 00:27:11.740
hundreds of millions
of dollars to develop

00:27:11.740 --> 00:27:14.710
next-generation records
search capabilities,

00:27:14.710 --> 00:27:17.500
in no small part
because of the FBI

00:27:17.500 --> 00:27:19.780
and DOJ's own
assertions pertaining

00:27:19.780 --> 00:27:24.530
to the dangerous poverty of
reliance upon ACS searches.

00:27:24.530 --> 00:27:27.310
For example, the FBI's sentinel
database and Investigative Data

00:27:27.310 --> 00:27:29.650
Warehouse, or IDW, which
has been referred to as a,

00:27:29.650 --> 00:27:31.790
quote, "Uber Google."

00:27:31.790 --> 00:27:36.410
are examples of some of these at
times wildly expensive, quote,

00:27:36.410 --> 00:27:38.320
"next-generation FBI
search platforms"

00:27:38.320 --> 00:27:42.720
that offer modern full-text
search capabilities.

00:27:42.720 --> 00:27:44.370
Yet, the Bureau
nearly always refuses

00:27:44.370 --> 00:27:46.560
to utilize these capabilities
for FOIA purposes.

00:27:46.560 --> 00:27:53.080
Instead, for FOIA searches, the
FBI insists upon using the ACS.

00:27:53.080 --> 00:27:55.620
So let's talk about the ACS.

00:27:55.620 --> 00:27:58.570
The ACS is comprised of three
primary search applications

00:27:58.570 --> 00:28:00.910
that the FBI can use
to perform to what

00:28:00.910 --> 00:28:03.730
amounts to searches of the CRS.

00:28:03.730 --> 00:28:08.980
One of these is the
Universal Index or UNI.

00:28:12.820 --> 00:28:17.080
Then, there is the ICM, or
Investigative Case Management,

00:28:17.080 --> 00:28:19.270
search application.

00:28:19.270 --> 00:28:23.410
And then there is the ECF,
or Electronic Case File.

00:28:23.410 --> 00:28:25.330
Now the FBI's default
FOIA search protocols

00:28:25.330 --> 00:28:29.230
involved utilization
of the UNI to search

00:28:29.230 --> 00:28:33.280
an arbitrarily-produced index,
or indices, of FBI CRS records

00:28:33.280 --> 00:28:34.525
mirrored within the ACS.

00:28:38.050 --> 00:28:40.060
The FBI has long
publicly insisted

00:28:40.060 --> 00:28:43.790
that a UNI index search alone
is adequate for FOIA purposes,

00:28:43.790 --> 00:28:45.490
and therefore, the
FBI nearly always

00:28:45.490 --> 00:28:48.160
refuses to utilize either
of ACS's other two search

00:28:48.160 --> 00:28:51.010
applications, the
ICM or the ECF.

00:28:56.830 --> 00:29:02.880
Internally, however--
well, you know,

00:29:02.880 --> 00:29:06.960
here is a training slide for
when to do an ECF search.

00:29:06.960 --> 00:29:11.070
Basically, in very rare cases or
if it's a high-visibility case

00:29:11.070 --> 00:29:12.750
so people might
notice that the FBI is

00:29:12.750 --> 00:29:14.910
conducting a deficient search.

00:29:18.200 --> 00:29:21.350
So yeah, we should
talk about the ECF.

00:29:21.350 --> 00:29:29.300
So the ACS's ECF application
conducts full-text searches

00:29:29.300 --> 00:29:29.825
of the CRS.

00:29:33.884 --> 00:29:35.300
It's not a great
full-text search.

00:29:35.300 --> 00:29:37.734
It's a 1995 full-text search.

00:29:37.734 --> 00:29:38.900
But it's a full-text search.

00:29:42.500 --> 00:29:46.370
And as opposed to the
UNI, which only searches

00:29:46.370 --> 00:29:50.630
several limited lists of
arbitrarily-indexed subjects

00:29:50.630 --> 00:29:51.890
of the CRS.

00:29:51.890 --> 00:29:54.650
The ECF performs a relatively
modern full-text search

00:29:54.650 --> 00:29:55.760
of the CRS.

00:29:55.760 --> 00:29:59.090
So on the one hand, the UNI,
it's just a list of indexes.

00:29:59.090 --> 00:30:02.000
It's just indices.

00:30:02.000 --> 00:30:05.570
The ECF, it conducts
a full-text search

00:30:05.570 --> 00:30:07.970
of everything in
the ACS, which is

00:30:07.970 --> 00:30:10.154
most of the things that
are in the CRS, which

00:30:10.154 --> 00:30:11.070
is what we want to do.

00:30:11.070 --> 00:30:13.680
We really want more
than the CRS but we

00:30:13.680 --> 00:30:15.079
don't get to deal with that.

00:30:15.079 --> 00:30:16.870
Right now, we're just
trying to do the CRS.

00:30:16.870 --> 00:30:20.210
We're trying to search the CRS.

00:30:20.210 --> 00:30:23.360
So, again, the ECF
full-text searches,

00:30:23.360 --> 00:30:25.790
it's not a modern
sentinel or IDW--

00:30:25.790 --> 00:30:28.930
Uber Google-- full-text
search but it's

00:30:28.930 --> 00:30:30.660
still a full-text search.

00:30:30.660 --> 00:30:34.460
However, declares the FBI's
FOIA chief, David Hardy,

00:30:34.460 --> 00:30:37.010
"only under extraordinary
circumstance--" oh, sorry.

00:30:37.010 --> 00:30:41.750
Here's a screen capture
of an ECF search.

00:30:41.750 --> 00:30:44.810
So this is what we
want them to do, right?

00:30:44.810 --> 00:30:50.230
Like, that's sort of how
low the bar is here, right?

00:30:50.230 --> 00:30:54.670
This is like, oh,
please, do this.

00:30:54.670 --> 00:31:01.670
But yeah, so David Harty,
the head of the FBI'S FOIA

00:31:01.670 --> 00:31:03.380
division, says
that, quote, "only

00:31:03.380 --> 00:31:04.910
under extraordinary
circumstances

00:31:04.910 --> 00:31:07.630
would the FBI conduct ECF
full-text searches of the CRS

00:31:07.630 --> 00:31:09.440
in response to a FOIA request."

00:31:09.440 --> 00:31:11.570
Somewhat amazingly,
the FBI insists

00:31:11.570 --> 00:31:13.580
that ECF full-text
searches are not

00:31:13.580 --> 00:31:17.510
more likely to locate responsive
records than UNI index

00:31:17.510 --> 00:31:19.970
searches.

00:31:19.970 --> 00:31:23.000
Further, the FBI argues
that ECF full-text searches

00:31:23.000 --> 00:31:25.670
for FOIA requests
are unduly burdensome

00:31:25.670 --> 00:31:29.480
and would be wasteful
of FBI resources.

00:31:29.480 --> 00:31:36.540
Declared FBI FOIA chief,
David Harty, in 2014,

00:31:36.540 --> 00:31:40.170
"full-text searches such as ECF
are considered an extraordinary

00:31:40.170 --> 00:31:43.380
measure that is unduly
burdensome and not reasonably

00:31:43.380 --> 00:31:46.840
likely to locate
responsive records."

00:31:46.840 --> 00:31:50.600
And "The net result
of a full-text search

00:31:50.600 --> 00:31:53.730
is typically a significant
use of time and resources

00:31:53.730 --> 00:31:56.260
that yield no additional
responsive information.

00:31:56.260 --> 00:31:59.370
As such, the ACS index
search of the CRS

00:31:59.370 --> 00:32:01.290
is the key to
locating information

00:32:01.290 --> 00:32:04.140
responsive to FOIA requests."

00:32:04.140 --> 00:32:07.230
So again, searching this
arbitrarily-produced index

00:32:07.230 --> 00:32:09.880
rather than a full-text
search is the key.

00:32:09.880 --> 00:32:14.540
And these are submitted
under penalty of perjury.

00:32:14.540 --> 00:32:17.040
The FBI's position here is akin
to suggesting that a search

00:32:17.040 --> 00:32:18.840
of a limited and
arbitrarily-produced card

00:32:18.840 --> 00:32:20.790
catalog at a vast library--

00:32:20.790 --> 00:32:25.390
150 million volume library--

00:32:25.390 --> 00:32:27.790
is as likely to locate book
pages containing a specified

00:32:27.790 --> 00:32:31.090
search term as a full-text
search of a database containing

00:32:31.090 --> 00:32:34.210
digitized versions of
most books in the library.

00:32:34.210 --> 00:32:36.070
I mean, simply,
the FBI's assertion

00:32:36.070 --> 00:32:38.980
is absurd on its face.

00:32:38.980 --> 00:32:44.380
Notably, and as one can
see, in this document--

00:32:44.380 --> 00:32:46.560
and I'll show you in a moment--

00:32:46.560 --> 00:32:50.150
this document from 2007, for
its own investigative non-FOIA

00:32:50.150 --> 00:32:54.150
purposes, the FBI routinely
uses the ECF application

00:32:54.150 --> 00:32:56.140
to conduct full-text
searches of the CRS

00:32:56.140 --> 00:32:58.140
and they don't think it's
that much of a burden.

00:32:58.140 --> 00:33:02.355
So, here, the FBI is--

00:33:02.355 --> 00:33:05.160
you know,
counter-terrorism division,

00:33:05.160 --> 00:33:07.890
they're very stressed that
animal rights activists are

00:33:07.890 --> 00:33:12.390
having their annual conference
at a convention center

00:33:12.390 --> 00:33:13.950
hotel in DC.

