A review of the ACS support
utilizing free text searches

00:34:21.835 --> 00:34:23.210
revealed the
following, which may

00:34:23.210 --> 00:34:24.860
be of interest to recipients.

00:34:24.860 --> 00:34:30.510
So prompt and limited review
of the ACS full-text search.

00:34:30.510 --> 00:34:34.850
So when the FBI is asked to use
ECF full-text searches for FOIA

00:34:34.850 --> 00:34:38.709
purposes, it is unduly
burdensome and doesn't work.

00:34:38.709 --> 00:34:40.250
It's redundant and
unduly burdensome.

00:34:40.250 --> 00:34:42.333
But when they need to do
it for their own purposes

00:34:42.333 --> 00:34:44.360
because they want
to see literally

00:34:44.360 --> 00:34:47.870
who the listed speakers coming
to town are, it's prompt,

00:34:47.870 --> 00:34:49.949
it's limited, it's
easy, and they do it.

00:34:49.949 --> 00:34:51.590
That's what they do.

00:34:51.590 --> 00:34:55.080
Because it's the only
thing that make sense.

00:34:55.080 --> 00:34:58.400
So, for FOIA purposes,
the FBI nearly always

00:34:58.400 --> 00:35:00.470
refuses to use any of
the full-text searches

00:35:00.470 --> 00:35:03.050
available to it,
whether it be the ACS's

00:35:03.050 --> 00:35:08.330
antiquated but functional ECF
or the Bureau's modern Sentinel

00:35:08.330 --> 00:35:10.760
and IDW platforms.

00:35:10.760 --> 00:35:13.970
Instead, as noted, the FBI's
default FOIA search protocol

00:35:13.970 --> 00:35:18.170
involves utilization
of the UNI to search

00:35:18.170 --> 00:35:21.080
an index or indices
of FBI CRS records

00:35:21.080 --> 00:35:23.390
mirrored within the ACS.

00:35:23.390 --> 00:35:30.316
And this is a screen capture
of a UNI, so an index search.

00:35:30.316 --> 00:35:31.940
The one we saw before
