This is the bad one.

00:35:35.510 --> 00:35:36.500
Yeah.

00:35:36.500 --> 00:35:38.990
So, right.

00:35:38.990 --> 00:35:41.660
So the FBI relies
upon index searches--

00:35:41.660 --> 00:35:46.760
indices-based searches-- to
conduct FOIA searches and this

00:35:46.760 --> 00:35:48.500
is a serious problem.

00:35:48.500 --> 00:35:52.790
First, in order for the
names or other search terms

00:35:52.790 --> 00:35:57.260
to be entered into an index,
hey have to be indexed.

00:35:57.260 --> 00:36:00.410
And these are not automated
indexing processes.

00:36:00.410 --> 00:36:04.010
It's literally a case
agent or, frequently,

00:36:04.010 --> 00:36:08.709
his or her secretary going
through with a pencil

00:36:08.709 --> 00:36:10.500
after they've completed
creating a document

00:36:10.500 --> 00:36:13.500
and saying this
name, this person.

00:36:13.500 --> 00:36:16.810
You got a 20-page report
and you want to go home.

00:36:16.810 --> 00:36:19.590
You're underlining names, you
pass it off to your secretary,

00:36:19.590 --> 00:36:21.900
he or she wants
to go home, right?

00:36:21.900 --> 00:36:25.430
And that's also-- so
it's very limited.

00:36:25.430 --> 00:36:26.970
It's not like every word.

00:36:26.970 --> 00:36:29.840
It's the teeny minority of
words that gets indexed.

00:36:29.840 --> 00:36:31.890
It's arbitrarily produced.

00:36:31.890 --> 00:36:33.900
Different people are
going to index differently

00:36:33.900 --> 00:36:35.130
and it's extremely limited.

00:36:39.850 --> 00:36:40.420
Yeah.

00:36:40.420 --> 00:36:42.820
Notably, this UNI
search, no records

00:36:42.820 --> 00:36:46.480
were found, as is the
case most of the time--

00:36:46.480 --> 00:36:48.550
two out of three times.

00:36:48.550 --> 00:36:53.110
Even David Harty, head
of FBI FOIA himself,

00:36:53.110 --> 00:36:55.570
concedes in court declarations
that the indexing of records

00:36:55.570 --> 00:37:00.064
by the FBI, which are
essential to FBI UNI searches,

00:37:00.064 --> 00:37:02.230
is characterized by a largely
discretionary and even

00:37:02.230 --> 00:37:05.372
arbitrary set of practices
not designed or suited

00:37:05.372 --> 00:37:07.330
for the purpose of
effectively locating records

00:37:07.330 --> 00:37:10.630
responsive to FOIA requests.

00:37:10.630 --> 00:37:15.870
So for example, this
is an FBI record

00:37:15.870 --> 00:37:20.640
about spying on the
anti-apartheid movement

00:37:20.640 --> 00:37:22.680
in the United States,
believing that

00:37:22.680 --> 00:37:24.750
the anti-apartheid
movement and Nelson Mandela

00:37:24.750 --> 00:37:26.700
are a Kremlin-directed
plot to undermine

00:37:26.700 --> 00:37:29.340
American national security.

00:37:29.340 --> 00:37:32.070
And this is what
indexing looks like.

00:37:32.070 --> 00:37:37.790
The agent, underlining the
name or a group or a phrase

00:37:37.790 --> 00:37:42.630
or whatever, and
then the secretary,

00:37:42.630 --> 00:37:48.900
once he or she is done entering,
manually, the selected search

00:37:48.900 --> 00:37:51.520
terms into the index,
we'll cross it out and say,

00:37:51.520 --> 00:37:52.930
hey, I did it.

00:37:52.930 --> 00:37:53.760
Right?

00:37:53.760 --> 00:38:01.690
So here's the same document
indexed by a different office.

00:38:01.690 --> 00:38:05.530
Notably, the ANC,
Mandela's political party,

00:38:05.530 --> 00:38:09.100
the anti-apartheid resistance
party, South Africa,

00:38:09.100 --> 00:38:10.060
it's indexed here.

00:38:10.060 --> 00:38:14.230
So, conceivably-- and we'll
get to why it probably

00:38:14.230 --> 00:38:17.530
wouldn't-- but conceivably, an
index-based search would come

00:38:17.530 --> 00:38:19.990
up with a hit here if you
were searching for records

00:38:19.990 --> 00:38:26.180
on the ANC but not here because
indexing is not only limited

00:38:26.180 --> 00:38:27.415
but arbitrary.

00:38:27.415 --> 00:38:29.540
Further, in the same
document, the exact same thing

00:38:29.540 --> 00:38:30.020
but reversed.

00:38:30.020 --> 00:38:32.270
Now the other document has
the index item and this one

00:38:32.270 --> 00:38:32.930
doesn't.

00:38:32.930 --> 00:38:35.960
South African president,
de Klerk, no index.

00:38:35.960 --> 00:38:39.170
South African president,
de Klerk, index.

00:38:39.170 --> 00:38:44.600
Again, not only is FBI indexing
a tremendously limited practice

00:38:44.600 --> 00:38:47.670
but it is also, especially
for FOIA search purposes--

00:38:47.670 --> 00:38:51.290
it works well for the
FBI's purpose of they

00:38:51.290 --> 00:38:53.450
want to be able to
retrieve the information

00:38:53.450 --> 00:38:55.880
for their
investigative purposes,

00:38:55.880 --> 00:38:59.260
but from a FOIA
perspective, I mean,

00:38:59.260 --> 00:39:03.430
it's, again, limited
and arbitrary.

00:39:03.430 --> 00:39:07.300
So, because there are
these inherent problems

00:39:07.300 --> 00:39:10.000
with FBI records
indexing procedures,

00:39:10.000 --> 00:39:12.400
UNI searches frequently fail
to locate a large percentage

00:39:12.400 --> 00:39:13.540
of responsive records.

00:39:13.540 --> 00:39:16.360
Simply, the overwhelming
majority of [INAUDIBLE] search

00:39:16.360 --> 00:39:18.310
terms just aren't indexed.

00:39:18.310 --> 00:39:20.770
So searches of the UNI
indices for these terms

00:39:20.770 --> 00:39:24.160
produce no responsive results.

00:39:24.160 --> 00:39:27.312
I mean, nothing is
indexed on this page.

00:39:27.312 --> 00:39:28.895
So if you want
something on this page,

00:39:28.895 --> 00:39:31.825
submit a FOIA
request for it, nope.

00:39:31.825 --> 00:39:32.950
Here you have these things.

00:39:32.950 --> 00:39:34.033
That's all that's indexed.

00:39:36.840 --> 00:39:42.150
But even within UNI searches,
not all UNI searches

00:39:42.150 --> 00:39:45.560
are created equally crappy.

00:39:45.560 --> 00:39:49.620
Some UNI searches are far
more inadequate than others.

00:39:49.620 --> 00:39:55.160
So UNI searches can be
performed in two primary ways.

00:39:55.160 --> 00:40:05.790
One is to perform a UNI index
search of its main file index

00:40:05.790 --> 00:40:08.750
and the other is to conduct
a search of the UNI's

00:40:08.750 --> 00:40:12.260
cross-reference index.

00:40:12.260 --> 00:40:20.129
So the FBI asserts
that a main file--

00:40:20.129 --> 00:40:22.420
something that would show up
in the main file indexed--

00:40:22.420 --> 00:40:23.086
is a meta-entry.

00:40:23.086 --> 00:40:23.700
A main file.

00:40:23.700 --> 00:40:26.200
It carries the name of someone
who is the subject of a file,

00:40:26.200 --> 00:40:26.650
right?

00:40:26.650 --> 00:40:28.316
If the FBI is really
interested in you--

00:40:28.316 --> 00:40:31.150
if you're being targeted by
the FBI-- if you're relevant--

00:40:31.150 --> 00:40:33.610
you're a main file.

00:40:33.610 --> 00:40:36.480
What's a cross-reference
according to the FBI?

00:40:36.480 --> 00:40:39.539
Cross-reference is defined as
a mere mention of or passing

00:40:39.539 --> 00:40:41.080
reference to the
subject of a request

00:40:41.080 --> 00:40:43.330
and files relating to other
individuals, organization,

00:40:43.330 --> 00:40:44.280
events, or activities.

00:40:44.280 --> 00:40:46.030
So let's say the FBI
is investigating you.

00:40:48.600 --> 00:40:52.074
You'd be a main file
according to this.

00:40:52.074 --> 00:40:53.990
The person you spoke to
at the ice cream store

00:40:53.990 --> 00:40:57.860
before you went to rob the
bank, allegedly, you know,

00:40:57.860 --> 00:41:00.330
that person might be
a cross-reference.

00:41:00.330 --> 00:41:00.920
Right?

00:41:00.920 --> 00:41:02.780
That's trivial.

00:41:02.780 --> 00:41:04.730
Insignificant.

00:41:04.730 --> 00:41:07.400
He's just really not important.

00:41:07.400 --> 00:41:10.604
Further, search the
FBI, our experience

00:41:10.604 --> 00:41:12.770
has shown that even when
cross-reference records are

00:41:12.770 --> 00:41:14.697
actually responsive
to a FOIA request,

00:41:14.697 --> 00:41:16.280
references usually
contain information

00:41:16.280 --> 00:41:18.200
similar to the information
already processed

00:41:18.200 --> 00:41:19.340
in a main file.

00:41:19.340 --> 00:41:21.840
So it's going to be redundant.

00:41:21.840 --> 00:41:23.340
It's insignificant.

00:41:23.340 --> 00:41:24.240
It's insignificant.

00:41:24.240 --> 00:41:25.080
It's redundant.

00:41:25.080 --> 00:41:27.860
You'd have gotten it anyway.

00:41:27.860 --> 00:41:33.190
So, with this as justification,
this main file versus

00:41:33.190 --> 00:41:37.300
cross-reference distinction,
the FBI's policy--

00:41:37.300 --> 00:41:41.230
their FOIA policy-- is not only
to limit searches of the CRS

00:41:41.230 --> 00:41:45.760
to the ACS's UNI application
but to limit those UNI searches

00:41:45.760 --> 00:41:48.265
solely to the UNI
applications main file index.

00:41:51.400 --> 00:41:55.750
there's an exception to
this policy so if you submit

00:41:55.750 --> 00:42:01.760
a request to the FBI and they
conduct a main file only search

00:42:01.760 --> 00:42:05.830
and you are sophisticated enough
and have the time to submit

00:42:05.830 --> 00:42:08.980
an appeal of that request to the
Department of Justice's Office

00:42:08.980 --> 00:42:12.880
of Information Policy
appealing the inadequate search

00:42:12.880 --> 00:42:15.527
because the FBI only conducted
a man file request and they

00:42:15.527 --> 00:42:17.610
should be conducting a
cross-reference request too

00:42:17.610 --> 00:42:21.467
and you know this, then OIP--

00:42:21.467 --> 00:42:23.800
the Department of Justice
Office of Information Policy--

00:42:23.800 --> 00:42:26.341
maybe nine months later, there's
a good chance that they will

00:42:26.341 --> 00:42:28.540
ultimately remand your
request back to the FBI--

00:42:28.540 --> 00:42:30.220
maybe it took them a year or
two years to get it to you

00:42:30.220 --> 00:42:31.904
in the first place--
the denial letter--

00:42:31.904 --> 00:42:33.070
the main file denial letter.

00:42:33.070 --> 00:42:33.580
You appeal.

00:42:33.580 --> 00:42:36.160
Nine months later, OIP remands.

00:42:36.160 --> 00:42:38.177
A year or two later,
maybe then the FBI

00:42:38.177 --> 00:42:39.760
does a cross-reference
search for you.

00:42:39.760 --> 00:42:42.500
But if you appeal
inadequate search

00:42:42.500 --> 00:42:45.740
based on the lack of a
cross-reference search,

00:42:45.740 --> 00:42:49.550
the FBI has a policy, they are
potentially open to conducting

00:42:49.550 --> 00:42:50.990
a cross-reference search.

00:42:50.990 --> 00:42:52.400
And also if you sue.

00:42:52.400 --> 00:42:53.869
The FBI will
automatically conduct

00:42:53.869 --> 00:42:55.910
a cross-reference search
because the FBI does not

00:42:55.910 --> 00:42:59.810
want this issue to be
before a court as case law

00:42:59.810 --> 00:43:02.029
because it's so grossly
violative of FOIA.

00:43:02.029 --> 00:43:04.070
The Freedom of Information
Act requires an agency

00:43:04.070 --> 00:43:05.778
to conduct searches
reasonably calculated

00:43:05.778 --> 00:43:07.490
to locate responsive records.

00:43:07.490 --> 00:43:10.010
This is not
reasonably calculated

00:43:10.010 --> 00:43:11.280
to locate responsive record.

00:43:11.280 --> 00:43:15.017
So if you sue, automatically,
the FBI wants to moot the issue

00:43:15.017 --> 00:43:17.100
and they will do a
cross-reference search for you.

00:43:20.670 --> 00:43:23.650
But for the vast majority
of FOIA requesters

00:43:23.650 --> 00:43:28.110
who neither appeal nor
litigate, they just

00:43:28.110 --> 00:43:30.726
get a no response of
records denial letter.

00:43:30.726 --> 00:43:32.850
We searched the main files
and didn't get anything.

00:43:32.850 --> 00:43:35.150
So the FBI tells us that
essentially everything a FOIA

00:43:35.150 --> 00:43:36.690
requester might
reasonably want is

00:43:36.690 --> 00:43:40.830
likely to come up under a UNI
main file search of the ACS

00:43:40.830 --> 00:43:43.350
and that a UNI cross-reference
search would be,

00:43:43.350 --> 00:43:48.240
again, wasteful and
redundant, which the FBI often

00:43:48.240 --> 00:43:49.849
continues, because
they are the FBI,

00:43:49.849 --> 00:43:52.140
therefore it constitutes a
threat to national security,

00:43:52.140 --> 00:43:55.900
because wasting the FBI's
time, thank you, Bin Laden.

00:43:55.900 --> 00:43:56.470
[? Right? ?]

00:43:56.470 --> 00:44:00.774
And so let's take a closer
look at how this actually

00:44:00.774 --> 00:44:01.690
plays out in practice.

00:44:01.690 --> 00:44:03.729
So we've seen what
the FBI has to say.

00:44:03.729 --> 00:44:05.270
Maybe just because
I'm cynical, let's

00:44:05.270 --> 00:44:10.910
take a closer look about
how it operates in reality.

00:44:10.910 --> 00:44:15.520
So again, the FBI makes clear,
at the initial administrative

00:44:15.520 --> 00:44:16.480
stage--

00:44:16.480 --> 00:44:18.850
so that means when you
submit a FOIA request--

00:44:18.850 --> 00:44:21.790
it is the FBI's policy to search
for and identify only main file

00:44:21.790 --> 00:44:25.340
records responsive
to FOIA requests.

00:44:25.340 --> 00:44:27.190
And here, surprisingly,
that search

00:44:27.190 --> 00:44:29.470
resulted in no
records being located.

00:44:32.560 --> 00:44:36.817
And again-- here.

00:44:36.817 --> 00:44:38.400
Searches are conducted
for main files.

00:44:38.400 --> 00:44:39.441
This is a training slide.

00:44:42.330 --> 00:44:44.100
Searches are conducted
for main files.

00:44:44.100 --> 00:44:46.206
Searches may also look
at reference files

00:44:46.206 --> 00:44:47.580
if you provide
information that's

00:44:47.580 --> 00:44:51.120
almost impossible to actually
meet their standards on

00:44:51.120 --> 00:44:52.450
or if you appeal.

00:44:52.450 --> 00:44:52.950
Right?

00:44:52.950 --> 00:44:54.366
And again, but
that's years later.

00:44:56.820 --> 00:44:59.360
So let's look at some
examples of how this plays out

00:44:59.360 --> 00:45:00.860
in real life.

00:45:00.860 --> 00:45:02.540
I submitted a Freedom
of Information Act

00:45:02.540 --> 00:45:05.600
request for records
on the pro fur lobby

00:45:05.600 --> 00:45:09.620
group, the anti-animal
rights lobby group, FC USA,

00:45:09.620 --> 00:45:11.680
or Fur Commission USA.

00:45:11.680 --> 00:45:14.570
2011, the FBI gives
me a denial letter--

00:45:14.570 --> 00:45:16.300
"unable to identify
main file records

00:45:16.300 --> 00:45:17.532
responsive to the FOIA."

00:45:17.532 --> 00:45:19.240
This is the same
language that everyone--

00:45:19.240 --> 00:45:21.490
that most people-- get when
they submit a FOIA request

00:45:21.490 --> 00:45:22.430
and they get a denial.

00:45:22.430 --> 00:45:25.010
People read it to think
that the FBI's saying

00:45:25.010 --> 00:45:27.500
they don't have anything.

00:45:27.500 --> 00:45:31.070
What it says is we looked and
we couldn't find anything.

00:45:31.070 --> 00:45:35.180
What it actually says is, we
looked in one database using

00:45:35.180 --> 00:45:38.090
one search methodology for
a very limited set of file

00:45:38.090 --> 00:45:40.460
types and oh yeah, we
didn't find anything.

00:45:40.460 --> 00:45:41.840
And by the way,
that's the point.

00:45:41.840 --> 00:45:43.280
But either way.

00:45:43.280 --> 00:45:47.090
So submitted my FOIA
request for FC USA.

00:45:47.090 --> 00:45:55.310
Unable to identify main file
records responsive to the FOIA.

00:45:55.310 --> 00:45:57.890
Then, with a
cross-reference search,

00:45:57.890 --> 00:46:02.000
because I do appeal
everything and I do litigate,

00:46:02.000 --> 00:46:05.040
you know, here is a document.

00:46:05.040 --> 00:46:09.590
And so, again, the FBI claims
that a cross-reference--

00:46:09.590 --> 00:46:12.870
and this comes up in a
cross-reference search

00:46:12.870 --> 00:46:17.100
of the UNI's cross-reference
indices for records on FC USA.

00:46:17.100 --> 00:46:19.740
So again, the FBI said
that cross-references are

00:46:19.740 --> 00:46:22.280
mere trivial passing reference.

00:46:22.280 --> 00:46:28.260
Here, the FBI is having a
meeting with the FC USA,

00:46:28.260 --> 00:46:31.990
introducing an intelligence
analyst at the FBI

00:46:31.990 --> 00:46:33.890
to a representative
from the FC USA--

00:46:33.890 --> 00:46:36.810
this fur industry lobby group--

00:46:36.810 --> 00:46:39.030
to be a routine point of
contact with the San Diego

00:46:39.030 --> 00:46:41.204
division of the FBI.

00:46:41.204 --> 00:46:42.870
Here, the police are
meeting with the FC

00:46:42.870 --> 00:46:46.230
USA, the meeting which
is hosted by FC USA

00:46:46.230 --> 00:46:47.790
and held at this resort.

00:46:47.790 --> 00:46:51.450
FC USA is holding
trainings for the FBI

00:46:51.450 --> 00:46:57.950
on how to deal
with puppy huggers.

00:46:57.950 --> 00:46:58.450
You know.

00:46:58.450 --> 00:47:01.370
And the FBI is giving
information to FC USA.

00:47:01.370 --> 00:47:04.340
They have a routine
back and forth.

00:47:04.340 --> 00:47:08.210
FC USA is teaching the FBI how
to use the FC USA's database

00:47:08.210 --> 00:47:12.627
of animal rights activists
because the FC USA isn't--

00:47:12.627 --> 00:47:14.210
they don't have any
of the limitations

00:47:14.210 --> 00:47:16.700
that the FBI ostensibly
has on spying

00:47:16.700 --> 00:47:19.520
on protected first
amendment activities.

00:47:19.520 --> 00:47:22.100
Review and discussing how law
enforcement and the FC USA

00:47:22.100 --> 00:47:23.720
can best complement each other.

00:47:23.720 --> 00:47:27.800
So hardly a trivial
or passing reference.

00:47:27.800 --> 00:47:30.880
Certainly not duplicative.

00:47:30.880 --> 00:47:33.470
No responsive records come
up under the main file

00:47:33.470 --> 00:47:35.970
and far from trivial.

00:47:35.970 --> 00:47:37.470
All right.

00:47:37.470 --> 00:47:40.240
Now, next.

00:47:40.240 --> 00:47:42.750
Submitted a FOIA request
on my dear friend,

00:47:42.750 --> 00:47:44.940
the legendary Steve Sipman.

00:47:44.940 --> 00:47:47.670
Steve Sipman, in 1977,
was one of two men--

00:47:47.670 --> 00:47:49.800
the other is Kenneth
LeVasseur-- who

00:47:49.800 --> 00:47:51.510
participated in the
first reported animal

00:47:51.510 --> 00:47:53.040
liberation in US history.

00:47:53.040 --> 00:47:55.920
The liberation of two dolphins
which were at a University

00:47:55.920 --> 00:47:59.040
of Hawaii at Navy Laboratory
in downtown Honolulu.

00:47:59.040 --> 00:48:03.480
They called themselves
the Undersea Railroad.

00:48:03.480 --> 00:48:06.090
Submitted this request
on Steve Sipman,

00:48:06.090 --> 00:48:09.360
unable to identify
responsive main file records.

00:48:09.360 --> 00:48:11.620
I also submitted a
request on Kenny--

00:48:11.620 --> 00:48:13.980
on Kenneth LeVasseur's records
because I got signatures

00:48:13.980 --> 00:48:15.950
from both of them.

00:48:15.950 --> 00:48:17.390
Kenny's came back.

00:48:17.390 --> 00:48:19.860
Now, so it turns
out, for something

00:48:19.860 --> 00:48:24.520
to come up as responsive as
a hit on the main file index,

00:48:24.520 --> 00:48:28.600
not only does it truly
need to be a subject

00:48:28.600 --> 00:48:33.130
but it literally needs to be
the top line of the subject.

00:48:33.130 --> 00:48:37.540
And, just like indexing, the
top line, it's arbitrary.

00:48:37.540 --> 00:48:39.720
It's up to the case agent.

00:48:39.720 --> 00:48:41.615
It could be alphabetical.

00:48:41.615 --> 00:48:42.990
It could be
perceived importance.

00:48:42.990 --> 00:48:44.561
It could be who
has a better beard.

00:48:44.561 --> 00:48:45.060
Right?

00:48:45.060 --> 00:48:46.770
Like, it's totally arbitrary.

00:48:46.770 --> 00:48:49.730
And it can change over the
course of an investigation.

00:48:49.730 --> 00:48:50.730
They can move it around.

00:48:50.730 --> 00:48:55.110
And literally, a request
for Sipman, no main files.

00:48:55.110 --> 00:48:58.990
A request for LeVasseur, main
file, because he's the top.

00:48:58.990 --> 00:49:00.420
You can see that
Sipman's indexed.

00:49:00.420 --> 00:49:02.380
You can see the line.

00:49:02.380 --> 00:49:04.270
But he's a cross-reference
because he's not

00:49:04.270 --> 00:49:05.350
the top, top line.

00:49:05.350 --> 00:49:10.514
And let's say the top line
had been Undersea Railroad.

00:49:10.514 --> 00:49:12.180
Then neither-- which
it easily could be.

00:49:12.180 --> 00:49:15.290
Then neither of them would
have come up as a main file.

00:49:15.290 --> 00:49:18.355
Let's say it had been theft of
two dolphins from the Kewalo

00:49:18.355 --> 00:49:20.480
Basin Marine Mammal
Laboratory as the top line.

00:49:20.480 --> 00:49:24.470
Then not even Undersea
Railroad would have come up.

00:49:24.470 --> 00:49:28.130
And not only does it
have to be in the subject

00:49:28.130 --> 00:49:34.130
and the top line, it has to
be all that the top line is.

00:49:34.130 --> 00:49:36.890
So this comes up as
a cross-reference

00:49:36.890 --> 00:49:38.450
for Nelson Mandela.

00:49:38.450 --> 00:49:41.800
So a main file search
on Nelson Mandela

00:49:41.800 --> 00:49:46.540
would not come up with a hit
for a visit of Nelson Mandela

00:49:46.540 --> 00:49:47.830
to the United States.

00:49:47.830 --> 00:49:49.810
This is a cross-reference
because it's not

00:49:49.810 --> 00:49:51.875
Nelson Mandela on
the top line, it's

00:49:51.875 --> 00:49:53.750
visit of Nelson Mandela
to the United States.

00:49:56.450 --> 00:49:59.960
Similarly, also, the
cross-reference release.

00:49:59.960 --> 00:50:02.620
Visit of Nelson Mandela to
accept his freedom award

00:50:02.620 --> 00:50:05.042
in Memphis, Tennessee.

00:50:05.042 --> 00:50:06.000
Not a main file search.

00:50:06.000 --> 00:50:07.740
If you submit a
request to the FBI

00:50:07.740 --> 00:50:12.060
and they conduct only an
index-based search and only

00:50:12.060 --> 00:50:16.060
a main file index-based search
and you asked for Nelson

00:50:16.060 --> 00:50:17.600
Mandela, you don't get this.

00:50:17.600 --> 00:50:19.970
You don't get it.

00:50:19.970 --> 00:50:22.700
And the records that I got on
Mandela showed that the FBI,

00:50:22.700 --> 00:50:27.700
in 1990, after Mandela got
out of prison after 27 years

00:50:27.700 --> 00:50:30.220
in prison in South Africa for
his anti-apartheid activities,

00:50:30.220 --> 00:50:32.896
the FBI was tasked with
protecting Mandela--

00:50:32.896 --> 00:50:34.270
when he came to
the United States

00:50:34.270 --> 00:50:36.700
to continue his
anti-apartheid efforts,

00:50:36.700 --> 00:50:38.680
the FBI was tasked with
protecting Mandela.

00:50:38.680 --> 00:50:40.179
And while they were
doing that, they

00:50:40.179 --> 00:50:42.460
took the opportunity to place
a confidential informant

00:50:42.460 --> 00:50:44.543
within Mandela's inner
circle in the United States

00:50:44.543 --> 00:50:47.800
to pass political information
to the FBI about Mandela

00:50:47.800 --> 00:50:50.200
and his anti-apartheid
associates activities

00:50:50.200 --> 00:50:53.560
in the United States.

00:50:53.560 --> 00:50:57.010
And then let's look at this one.

00:50:57.010 --> 00:50:59.260
TSBR, the Texas Society
for Biomedical Research,

00:50:59.260 --> 00:51:04.320
another lobby group for
the biomedical industry,

00:51:04.320 --> 00:51:07.660
unable to identify
main file records.

00:51:07.660 --> 00:51:08.210
OK?

00:51:08.210 --> 00:51:10.545
What do we got?

00:51:10.545 --> 00:51:11.515
I appealed.

00:51:14.180 --> 00:51:15.180
Let's look at the dates.

00:51:15.180 --> 00:51:19.540
So I submitted the request
maybe a year before that.

00:51:19.540 --> 00:51:22.060
They come back, tell me
they don't have anything--

00:51:22.060 --> 00:51:24.310
unable to identify main files.

00:51:24.310 --> 00:51:29.770
Now in 2012, after
I appealed, DOJ OIP

00:51:29.770 --> 00:51:32.680
says, all right,
all right, yeah, OK.

00:51:32.680 --> 00:51:36.261
We'll remand it to the FBI
to look for cross-references.

00:51:36.261 --> 00:51:36.760
OK.

00:51:39.520 --> 00:51:41.160
Behold, they find some.

00:51:41.160 --> 00:51:42.910
I get them a couple--
you know, I get them

00:51:42.910 --> 00:51:45.590
in February of this year.

00:51:45.590 --> 00:51:47.690
Six pages.

00:51:47.690 --> 00:51:48.920
You know.

00:51:48.920 --> 00:51:51.770
And the first of the documents.

00:51:51.770 --> 00:51:55.350
You know, it's more than a
passing fleeting reference.

00:51:55.350 --> 00:51:59.310
The FBI is getting an alert
from the Texas Society

00:51:59.310 --> 00:52:01.540
for Biomedical Research.

00:52:01.540 --> 00:52:03.870
TSBR's been monitoring
animal rights hotlines

00:52:03.870 --> 00:52:08.230
and it's rumored that the
widely-broadcast protests that

00:52:08.230 --> 00:52:10.125
