01:10:49.925 --> 01:10:53.170
AUDIENCE: When you
file a FOIA request,

01:10:53.170 --> 01:10:54.685
there's a section
in which it asks

01:10:54.685 --> 01:10:56.060
you something
along the lines of,

01:10:56.060 --> 01:10:57.260
how hard do you want us to try?

01:10:57.260 --> 01:10:58.760
I.e., how much money
are you willing

01:10:58.760 --> 01:11:01.950
to spend on us going above
and beyond a normal lookup?

01:11:01.950 --> 01:11:03.090
What's that actually for?

01:11:03.090 --> 01:11:06.099
If I said I'm willing to
spend $1,000, what happens?

01:11:06.099 --> 01:11:06.890
RYAN SHAPIRO: Sure.

01:11:06.890 --> 01:11:08.250
That's a great question.

01:11:08.250 --> 01:11:12.710
So they're not really asking
how hard you want them to try.

01:11:12.710 --> 01:11:16.190
Just as the agencies,
and especially the FBI,

01:11:16.190 --> 01:11:19.460
use deficient FOIA search
protocols as a barrier

01:11:19.460 --> 01:11:23.210
to preventing people from
conducting successful FOIA

01:11:23.210 --> 01:11:27.290
requests, agencies, certainly
very much including the FBI,

01:11:27.290 --> 01:11:29.810
use FOIA fees as a
way to do the same.

01:11:29.810 --> 01:11:32.310
So they're not actually saying
they're going to work harder.

01:11:32.310 --> 01:11:34.490
The FBI is interested
in preventing people

01:11:34.490 --> 01:11:36.590
from submitting
successful FOIA requests.

01:11:36.590 --> 01:11:41.150
And so when they're saying, how
much are you willing to pay,

01:11:41.150 --> 01:11:44.240
they're trying to figure out
if they can make you go away.

01:11:44.240 --> 01:11:45.200
Can they make you go
away because they're

01:11:45.200 --> 01:11:45.890
taking too long?

01:11:45.890 --> 01:11:47.150
Can they make you go
away because they're not

01:11:47.150 --> 01:11:48.139
locating the records?

01:11:48.139 --> 01:11:50.180
Can they make you go away
because they're saying,

01:11:50.180 --> 01:11:52.380
we're going to charge you
a lot of money for it.

01:11:52.380 --> 01:11:54.838
And there's all sorts of fees
that the agencies can charge.

01:11:54.838 --> 01:11:59.360
They can charge for a search,
review, or duplication fees.

01:11:59.360 --> 01:12:02.540
And fees, I mean, since FOIA
was amended in '74, I mean,

01:12:02.540 --> 01:12:09.560
there's been a lot of talk about
how agencies use fees as speed

01:12:09.560 --> 01:12:10.454
bumps on--

01:12:10.454 --> 01:12:12.370
I'm trying to remember
the metaphor they used.

01:12:12.370 --> 01:12:15.020
Something like speed bumps on
the highway for information.

01:12:15.020 --> 01:12:17.600
Either way, so
what's going on there

01:12:17.600 --> 01:12:20.780
is the agency is trying
to scare you off.

01:12:20.780 --> 01:12:22.490
What I would
encourage you to do--

01:12:22.490 --> 01:12:26.030
and I don't know this
individual situation,

01:12:26.030 --> 01:12:31.810
but FOIA requesters can
ask for a fee waiver

01:12:31.810 --> 01:12:37.010
and they can also ask for
placement in a particular fee

01:12:37.010 --> 01:12:37.770
category.

01:12:37.770 --> 01:12:39.860
So if someone's a
student, someone

01:12:39.860 --> 01:12:43.610
should request placement
in the educational--

01:12:43.610 --> 01:12:46.550
what one should do if they're
looking for these ways to get

01:12:46.550 --> 01:12:48.925
out of paying fees-- legitimate
ways to get out of paying

01:12:48.925 --> 01:12:50.270
fees--

01:12:50.270 --> 01:12:52.880
I request a waiver of fees
and I also request placement

01:12:52.880 --> 01:12:55.400
in x, y, or z fee category.

01:12:55.400 --> 01:12:59.135
So educational fee
category or representative

01:12:59.135 --> 01:13:02.300
of the news media fee category.

01:13:02.300 --> 01:13:04.647
This way, agencies-- if
you get either of those,

01:13:04.647 --> 01:13:06.230
the agencies can't
charge search fees,

01:13:06.230 --> 01:13:10.380
and search fees can be $45 an
hour and the agency can charge

01:13:10.380 --> 01:13:10.880
as much--

01:13:10.880 --> 01:13:14.060
they can say it's
going to take us

01:13:14.060 --> 01:13:17.300
1,000 hours to search for
stuff that you're requesting.

01:13:17.300 --> 01:13:19.405
We don't know if we're
going to find anything

01:13:19.405 --> 01:13:21.530
but you're going to owe us
the money no matter what

01:13:21.530 --> 01:13:23.300
and you've got to pay
half of it up front

01:13:23.300 --> 01:13:27.110
and a search requires
this level of analyst

01:13:27.110 --> 01:13:29.810
and so that's $45 an hour so
you owe us a whole lot of money.

01:13:29.810 --> 01:13:31.950
Are you sure you want
to go forward with this?

01:13:31.950 --> 01:13:34.915
And so if you can get either an
educational requester status--

01:13:34.915 --> 01:13:36.410
fee requester--

01:13:36.410 --> 01:13:40.130
like fee status--
or representative

01:13:40.130 --> 01:13:42.560
of the news media,
agencies are no longer

01:13:42.560 --> 01:13:46.490
allowed to assess search
fees or review fees

01:13:46.490 --> 01:13:49.510
and then you're stuck only
with duplication fees.

01:13:49.510 --> 01:13:52.790
You know, which aren't really
going to go above about like

01:13:52.790 --> 01:13:56.420
$0.10 a page, which, while
it can still be onerous,

01:13:56.420 --> 01:14:01.200
it's not $45 an hour unlimited
and independent of whether

01:14:01.200 --> 01:14:02.344
or not you get records.

